================================================================================
  1. SEVERITY LEVELS
================================================================================

  +-------+------------------+----------------+---------------+----------------+
  | Level | Name             | Response Time  | Update Freq   | Examples       |
  +-------+------------------+----------------+---------------+----------------+
  | P0    | CRITICAL         | 15 minutes     | Every 30 min  | Full outage,   |
  |       | (Site Down)      |                |               | data loss,     |
  |       |                  |                |               | security       |
  |       |                  |                |               | breach         |
  +-------+------------------+----------------+---------------+----------------+
  | P1    | HIGH             | 30 minutes     | Every 1 hour  | Major feature  |
  |       | (Major Feature   |                |               | broken (auth,  |
  |       |  Broken)         |                |               | notifications, |
  |       |                  |                |               | task CRUD),    |
  |       |                  |                |               | >10% users     |
  |       |                  |                |               | affected       |
  +-------+------------------+----------------+---------------+----------------+
  | P2    | MEDIUM           | 2 hours        | Every 4 hours | Minor feature  |
  |       | (Minor Issue)    |                |               | broken, single |
  |       |                  |                |               | channel down,  |
  |       |                  |                |               | slow perf,     |
  |       |                  |                |               | <10% users     |
  +-------+------------------+----------------+---------------+----------------+
  | P3    | LOW              | Next business  | On resolution | Cosmetic bugs, |
  |       | (Cosmetic)       | day            |               | typos, minor   |
  |       |                  |                |               | UI glitches,   |
  |       |                  |                |               | non-blocking   |
  +-------+------------------+----------------+---------------+----------------+

  ESCALATION RULES:
  - P0: Immediately notify all engineering + CTO. All hands on deck.
  - P1: Notify on-call engineer + engineering lead. Pull in help if no
    progress in 1 hour.
  - P2: On-call engineer handles. Escalate to P1 if not resolved in 4 hours.
  - P3: Track in issue tracker. Fix in next sprint.

  AUTO-ESCALATION:
  - If P1 not acknowledged in 30 min -> escalate to P0.
  - If P2 not acknowledged in 2 hours -> escalate to P1.
  - Sentry alert thresholds trigger auto-escalation (configured in Sentry).

================================================================================
  2. ON-CALL ROTATION TEMPLATE
================================================================================

  ROTATION SCHEDULE:
  - Weekly rotation, handoff every Monday at 09:00 IST
  - Primary on-call: first responder, expected to acknowledge within SLA
  - Secondary on-call: backup if primary does not respond within 15 min
  - On-call hours: 24/7 for P0/P1, business hours only for P2/P3

  WEEK TEMPLATE:
  +----------+-------------------+---------------------+
  | Week     | Primary On-Call   | Secondary On-Call    |
  +----------+-------------------+---------------------+
  | Week 1   | Engineer A        | Engineer B           |
  | Week 2   | Engineer B        | Engineer C           |
  | Week 3   | Engineer C        | Engineer A           |
  | Week 4   | Engineer A        | Engineer B           |
  +----------+-------------------+---------------------+

  ON-CALL RESPONSIBILITIES:
  - Monitor Sentry and Grafana dashboards
  - Acknowledge alerts within SLA
  - Triage and begin investigation
  - Communicate status updates per severity schedule
  - Hand off context cleanly if shift ends during an incident
  - Write postmortem if incident was P0 or P1

  ON-CALL TOOLKIT:
  - Sentry dashboard: https://sentry.unjynx.app
  - Grafana dashboard: https://grafana.unjynx.app
  - Docker access: SSH to production host or Docker Desktop (dev)
  - Database access: pgAdmin or psql via SSH tunnel
  - BullMQ dashboard: Bull Board at /admin/queues (auth required)
  - Logto admin: https://logto.unjynx.app/console
  - Log aggregation: Loki via Grafana

================================================================================
  3. INCIDENT RESPONSE PROCESS
================================================================================

  PHASE 1: DETECT (0-5 minutes)
  ------------------------------
  Incident detected via:
  - Sentry alert (error spike, new issue)
  - Grafana alert (CPU, memory, disk, response time threshold)
  - User report (support email, in-app feedback, social media)
  - Automated health check failure (uptime monitor)
  - BullMQ stalled job alert

  Actions:
  1. Acknowledge the alert in the monitoring system
  2. Open an incident channel (Slack #incident-YYYY-MM-DD-N or Discord)
  3. Assign initial severity level based on the matrix above
  4. Timestamp everything from this point forward

  PHASE 2: TRIAGE (5-15 minutes)
  --------------------------------
  Goal: Understand what is broken and how many users are affected.

  Actions:
  1. Check Sentry for error details:
     - Error message, stack trace, affected endpoint
     - Number of events, number of affected users
     - First seen vs. last seen (is it new or recurring?)
  2. Check Grafana for system health:
     - API response times (p50, p95, p99)
     - Error rate percentage
     - CPU, memory, disk usage
     - Database connection pool utilization
     - BullMQ queue depth and failure rate
  3. Check recent deployments:
     - When was the last deploy? (git log, CI/CD history)
     - What changed? (git diff between current and previous release)
     - Correlation: did the issue start after the deploy?
  4. Check external dependencies:
     - Gupshup (WhatsApp) status page
     - MSG91 (SMS) status page
     - SendGrid (email) status page
     - Telegram Bot API status
  5. Determine blast radius:
     - All users or subset?
     - All platforms or specific (Android/iOS)?
     - All regions or specific?
  6. Update severity level if initial assessment was wrong

  PHASE 3: COMMUNICATE (ongoing throughout incident)
  ---------------------------------------------------
  Actions:
  1. Post initial status update (use templates in Section 6)
  2. Update status page if user-facing impact exists
  3. Notify stakeholders per severity level:
     - P0: All engineering, CTO, status page, social media
     - P1: Engineering lead, status page
     - P2: Incident channel only
     - P3: Issue tracker only
  4. Continue updates at the frequency defined by severity level
  5. Always include: what is known, what is being done, ETA if available

  PHASE 4: FIX (variable duration)
  ----------------------------------
  Strategy priority:
  1. MITIGATE first (reduce impact even if root cause unknown)
     - Restart failed containers
     - Scale up resources
     - Enable maintenance mode for affected feature
     - Redirect traffic away from failing service
  2. INVESTIGATE root cause
     - Follow the relevant scenario guide in Section 4
     - Check logs (Loki via Grafana, docker logs)
     - Reproduce in staging if possible
     - Bisect recent changes if deploy-related
  3. FIX the root cause
     - Apply the fix
     - Deploy to staging first if time allows
     - Deploy to production
     - Verify the fix resolves the issue
  4. MONITOR for recurrence
     - Watch error rates for 30 minutes after fix
     - Verify affected metrics return to baseline

  PHASE 5: POSTMORTEM (within 48 hours of resolution)
  -----------------------------------------------------
  Required for all P0 and P1 incidents. Optional for P2.
  See Section 7 for the postmortem template.

  Actions:
  1. Schedule postmortem meeting (within 48 hours)
  2. Primary on-call writes the initial draft
  3. All involved engineers review and contribute
  4. Identify action items with owners and deadlines
  5. Share with full engineering team
  6. Track action items to completion

================================================================================
  4. COMMON SCENARIOS & FIXES
================================================================================

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  SCENARIO 4.1: BACKEND UNRESPONSIVE (API returns 5xx or times out)
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  SYMPTOMS:
  - Mobile app shows "Connection error" or loading spinner indefinitely
  - Grafana: API response time spikes, error rate > 5%
  - Sentry: ECONNREFUSED, ETIMEDOUT, or 502/503 errors

  DIAGNOSTIC STEPS:

  1. Check if containers are running:
     $ docker ps --format "table {{.Names}}\t{{.Status}}\t{{.Ports}}"

     Expected: All 10 containers UP (api, postgres, valkey, logto, logto-db,
     minio, prometheus, grafana, loki, mailpit)

  2. If api container is down, check logs:
     $ docker logs unjynx-api --tail 100

  3. If api is running but unresponsive, check resource usage:
     $ docker stats --no-stream

  4. Check PostgreSQL connectivity:
     $ docker exec unjynx-postgres pg_isready -U unjynx
     Expected: "accepting connections"

  5. Check Valkey (Redis) connectivity:
     $ docker exec unjynx-valkey valkey-cli ping
     Expected: "PONG"

  6. Check if the issue is network-level:
     $ curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" http://localhost:3000/health
     Expected: 200

  FIXES:

  A. Container crashed -> Restart it:
     $ docker restart unjynx-api

  B. All containers down -> Restart the stack:
     $ docker compose up -d

  C. PostgreSQL out of connections:
     $ docker exec unjynx-postgres psql -U unjynx -c \
       "SELECT count(*) FROM pg_stat_activity;"
     If near max_connections (100 default):
     $ docker restart unjynx-postgres
     Then restart api:
     $ docker restart unjynx-api

  D. Valkey out of memory:
     $ docker exec unjynx-valkey valkey-cli info memory
     If used_memory is near maxmemory:
     $ docker exec unjynx-valkey valkey-cli FLUSHDB
     (WARNING: clears all cached data and BullMQ jobs. Use only if critical.)

  E. Disk full:
     $ df -h
     If disk > 90%:
     - Prune Docker: docker system prune -f
     - Rotate logs: truncate -s 0 /var/log/docker/*.log
     - Remove old images: docker image prune -a -f

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  SCENARIO 4.2: HIGH ERROR RATE (>5% of requests failing)
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  SYMPTOMS:
  - Sentry: spike in new or existing error events
  - Grafana: error_rate gauge exceeds 5% threshold
  - Users reporting intermittent failures

  DIAGNOSTIC STEPS:

  1. Check Sentry for the dominant error:
     - Go to Sentry dashboard -> Issues -> Sort by Events (descending)
     - Identify: which endpoint, which error, which release

  2. Check if error correlates with a recent deploy:
     $ git log --oneline -10
     Compare timestamps with Sentry "First Seen"

  3. Tail live logs:
     $ docker logs unjynx-api --follow --tail 50

  4. Check if it is a specific endpoint:
     - Grafana: request rate by route panel
     - Identify if one route is generating all errors

  FIXES:

  A. Bad deploy -> Roll back (see Section 5)

  B. Specific endpoint failing -> Check that endpoint's:
     - Database query (slow query? missing index? schema mismatch?)
     - External API call (provider down? rate limited?)
     - Input validation (new edge case in user input?)

  C. Transient error (network blip, temporary overload):
     - Monitor for 10 minutes
     - If self-resolving, document and close
     - If recurring, investigate connection pooling / retry logic

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  SCENARIO 4.3: AUTH FAILURES (users cannot log in)
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  SYMPTOMS:
  - Mobile app shows "Authentication failed" or "Session expired"
  - Sentry: 401/403 errors on /api/v1/auth/* endpoints
  - Logto admin console inaccessible

  DIAGNOSTIC STEPS:

  1. Check Logto container health:
     $ docker logs unjynx-logto --tail 50
     $ curl -s http://localhost:3301/oidc/.well-known/openid-configuration

  2. Check Logto database:
     $ docker exec unjynx-logto-db pg_isready -U logto
     $ docker logs unjynx-logto-db --tail 20

  3. Check JWT validation:
     - Verify LOGTO_ENDPOINT in api .env matches running Logto URL
     - Verify LOGTO_RESOURCE matches the API resource in Logto console
     - Check if JWT signing keys have rotated unexpectedly

  4. Check token expiry configuration:
     - Access token TTL: 15 minutes (default)
     - Refresh token TTL: 7 days (default)
     - If clock skew between servers > 30s, tokens may be rejected

  FIXES:

  A. Logto container down -> Restart:
     $ docker restart unjynx-logto

  B. Logto DB corrupted -> Restore from backup:
     $ docker restart unjynx-logto-db
     If that fails, re-seed:
     $ docker exec unjynx-logto-db psql -U logto -f /docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/init.sql

  C. JWT key rotation issue:
     - Check Logto admin console -> Signing Keys
     - If keys rotated, api server needs restart to fetch new JWKS:
       $ docker restart unjynx-api

  D. Clock skew:
     $ date && docker exec unjynx-api date
     If > 30s difference, sync NTP:
     $ sudo ntpdate -u pool.ntp.org

  E. M2M token expired (backend-to-Logto communication):
     - Check LOGTO_M2M_APP_ID and LOGTO_M2M_APP_SECRET in .env
     - Verify M2M application exists in Logto console
     - Restart api to force new M2M token fetch

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  SCENARIO 4.4: NOTIFICATION DELIVERY FAILURES
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  SYMPTOMS:
  - Users report not receiving reminders on WhatsApp/Telegram/SMS/Email
  - BullMQ dashboard shows failed jobs or growing queue depth
  - Delivery attempt logs show repeated failures

  DIAGNOSTIC STEPS:

  1. Check BullMQ queue health:
     - Open Bull Board: http://localhost:3000/admin/queues
     - Check each queue: waiting, active, completed, failed counts
     - Check failed jobs for error messages

  2. Check specific channel adapter:

     WhatsApp (Gupshup):
     - Verify GUPSHUP_API_KEY in .env
     - Check Gupshup dashboard for delivery status
     - Verify template approval status (Meta requires pre-approved templates)
     - Check if user's WhatsApp number is valid and opted in

     Telegram (Bot API):
     - Verify TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN in .env
     - Test: curl https://api.telegram.org/bot<TOKEN>/getMe
     - Check if user has started a conversation with the bot
     - Verify webhook URL is correctly set

     SMS (MSG91):
     - Verify MSG91_AUTH_KEY in .env
     - Check MSG91 dashboard for delivery reports
     - Verify DLT registration (required in India)
     - Check if sender ID is approved

     Email (SendGrid):
     - Verify SENDGRID_API_KEY in .env
     - Check SendGrid dashboard for bounces/blocks
     - Verify sender domain authentication (SPF, DKIM, DMARC)
     - Check if email is landing in spam

     Discord (Bot API):
     - Verify DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN in .env
     - Check if bot is in the user's server
     - Verify bot has Send Messages permission

     Slack (Web API):
     - Verify SLACK_BOT_TOKEN in .env
     - Check if bot is in the user's workspace
     - Verify OAuth scopes include chat:write

  3. Check Valkey (queue backend):
     $ docker exec unjynx-valkey valkey-cli info clients
     $ docker exec unjynx-valkey valkey-cli DBSIZE

  4. Check scheduler:
     - Is the cron scheduler running?
     $ docker logs unjynx-api --tail 50 | grep -i "cron\|scheduler"
     - Are jobs being enqueued?
     $ docker exec unjynx-valkey valkey-cli LLEN bull:whatsapp:wait

  FIXES:

  A. Stalled BullMQ jobs -> Retry failed jobs:
     - Via Bull Board UI: select failed jobs -> Retry
     - Or programmatically via API endpoint

  B. Channel provider outage -> Check status pages:
     - Gupshup: https://status.gupshup.io
     - MSG91: https://status.msg91.com
     - SendGrid: https://status.sendgrid.com
     - Switch to backup channel if available (escalation chain)

  C. Rate limiting by provider:
     - Check current rate limits in provider dashboard
     - Reduce send rate in BullMQ worker configuration
     - Implement backoff: exponential retry with jitter

  D. Valkey down -> Restart:
     $ docker restart unjynx-valkey
     Note: In-memory jobs will be lost. Scheduler will re-enqueue
     upcoming reminders on next cron cycle.

  E. Template not approved (WhatsApp):
     - Submit template via Gupshup dashboard
     - Wait for Meta approval (usually 24-48 hours)
     - Fall back to session messages if user initiated conversation

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  SCENARIO 4.5: DATABASE SLOW (queries taking >1s)
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  SYMPTOMS:
  - API response times elevated (p95 > 500ms, p99 > 2s)
  - Grafana: database query duration panel shows spikes
  - Sentry: timeout errors on database-heavy endpoints

  DIAGNOSTIC STEPS:

  1. Check slow query log:
     $ docker exec unjynx-postgres psql -U unjynx -c \
       "SELECT pid, now() - pg_stat_activity.query_start AS duration, query
        FROM pg_stat_activity
        WHERE state = 'active' AND query_start < now() - interval '1 second'
        ORDER BY duration DESC LIMIT 10;"

  2. Check connection pool utilization:
     $ docker exec unjynx-postgres psql -U unjynx -c \
       "SELECT count(*), state FROM pg_stat_activity GROUP BY state;"

  3. Check table sizes and bloat:
     $ docker exec unjynx-postgres psql -U unjynx -c \
       "SELECT relname, pg_size_pretty(pg_total_relation_size(relid))
        FROM pg_catalog.pg_statio_user_tables
        ORDER BY pg_total_relation_size(relid) DESC LIMIT 10;"

  4. Check disk space:
     $ docker exec unjynx-postgres df -h /var/lib/postgresql/data

  5. Check for missing indexes:
     $ docker exec unjynx-postgres psql -U unjynx -c \
       "SELECT schemaname, relname, seq_scan, seq_tup_read, idx_scan
        FROM pg_stat_user_tables
        WHERE seq_scan > 100 AND idx_scan < 10
        ORDER BY seq_tup_read DESC LIMIT 10;"

  6. Check for lock contention:
     $ docker exec unjynx-postgres psql -U unjynx -c \
       "SELECT blocked_locks.pid AS blocked_pid,
               blocking_locks.pid AS blocking_pid,
               blocked_activity.query AS blocked_query
        FROM pg_catalog.pg_locks blocked_locks
        JOIN pg_catalog.pg_locks blocking_locks
          ON blocking_locks.locktype = blocked_locks.locktype
        JOIN pg_catalog.pg_stat_activity blocked_activity
          ON blocked_activity.pid = blocked_locks.pid
        JOIN pg_catalog.pg_stat_activity blocking_activity
          ON blocking_activity.pid = blocking_locks.pid
        WHERE NOT blocked_locks.granted LIMIT 5;"

  FIXES:

  A. Long-running query -> Kill it:
     $ docker exec unjynx-postgres psql -U unjynx -c \
       "SELECT pg_terminate_backend(<PID>);"

  B. Missing index -> Add it:
     - Identify the slow query
     - Add appropriate index via Drizzle migration
     - Deploy migration (see rollback procedure for safety)

  C. Table bloat -> Vacuum:
     $ docker exec unjynx-postgres psql -U unjynx -c \
       "VACUUM ANALYZE <table_name>;"
     For aggressive cleanup:
     $ docker exec unjynx-postgres psql -U unjynx -c \
       "VACUUM FULL <table_name>;"
     WARNING: VACUUM FULL locks the table. Run during low-traffic window.

  D. Connection pool exhausted:
     - Increase max_connections in postgresql.conf
     - Or reduce pool size in Drizzle connection config
     - Restart PostgreSQL:
       $ docker restart unjynx-postgres

  E. Disk space critical:
     - Remove old WAL files: pg_archivecleanup
     - Truncate large log tables
     - Increase disk allocation in Docker volume

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  SCENARIO 4.6: OUT OF MEMORY (OOM)
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  SYMPTOMS:
  - Container killed by OOM killer (docker logs show "Killed")
  - docker stats shows container at memory limit
  - API becomes unresponsive, then container restarts

  DIAGNOSTIC STEPS:

  1. Check which container was OOM-killed:
     $ docker inspect --format='{{.State.OOMKilled}}' unjynx-api
     $ docker inspect --format='{{.State.OOMKilled}}' unjynx-postgres

  2. Check current memory usage:
     $ docker stats --no-stream --format \
       "table {{.Name}}\t{{.MemUsage}}\t{{.MemPerc}}"

  3. Check for memory leaks in api:
     - Sentry: look for increasing memory trend in performance dashboard
     - Node.js heap dump (if accessible):
       $ docker exec unjynx-api node -e "console.log(process.memoryUsage())"

  4. Check BullMQ worker memory:
     - Large number of concurrent workers can consume significant memory
     - Check worker concurrency settings

  FIXES:

  A. Immediate relief -> Restart the container:
     $ docker restart unjynx-api

  B. Increase memory limit in docker-compose.yml:
     deploy:
       resources:
         limits:
           memory: 1G    # increase from 512M
     Then: $ docker compose up -d unjynx-api

  C. Node.js memory limit:
     Add to api Dockerfile or docker-compose command:
     command: node --max-old-space-size=768 dist/index.js

  D. BullMQ worker optimization:
     - Reduce concurrency per queue (default 5, try 2)
     - Ensure completed/failed jobs are cleaned up (removeOnComplete/Fail)
     - Check for job data that is too large (attachments, full task objects)

  E. PostgreSQL shared_buffers too high:
     - Default 128MB may be too high for container with 256MB limit
     - Adjust in postgresql.conf: shared_buffers = 64MB
     - Restart: $ docker restart unjynx-postgres

  F. Memory leak investigation:
     - Enable Node.js heap snapshots: --inspect flag
     - Compare snapshots over time to identify growing objects
     - Common leak sources: unclosed database connections, event listener
       accumulation, large in-memory caches without TTL

================================================================================
  5. ROLLBACK PROCEDURES
================================================================================

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  5.1: SHOREBIRD OTA PATCH REVERT (Flutter mobile app)
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Shorebird allows instant rollback of Flutter patches without going through
  the App Store / Play Store review process.

  STEPS:
  1. List current patches:
     $ shorebird patch list --app-id com.metaminds.unjynx

  2. Identify the bad patch number

  3. Revert to previous patch:
     $ shorebird patch delete --app-id com.metaminds.unjynx --patch <NUMBER>

  4. If you need to revert to the base release (no patches):
     $ shorebird patch delete --app-id com.metaminds.unjynx --all

  5. Verify: open the app and confirm it is running the previous version

  NOTES:
  - Shorebird patches propagate within minutes
  - Users must open the app to receive the rollback
  - Only Dart code can be patched via Shorebird (not native code)
  - If the issue is in native code, you must submit a new build to stores

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  5.2: DOCKER IMAGE ROLLBACK (Backend API)
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  STEPS:
  1. List available images:
     $ docker images unjynx-api --format "table {{.Tag}}\t{{.CreatedAt}}"

  2. Identify the last known good tag/SHA

  3. Update docker-compose.yml image tag:
     image: unjynx-api:<GOOD_TAG>

  4. Deploy the rollback:
     $ docker compose up -d unjynx-api

  5. Verify:
     $ curl http://localhost:3000/health
     $ docker logs unjynx-api --tail 20

  FOR CI/CD DEPLOYMENTS:
  1. Go to GitHub Actions -> select the last successful deployment workflow
  2. Click "Re-run all jobs" to redeploy the previous version
  3. Or manually trigger deployment with the previous commit SHA

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  5.3: DATABASE MIGRATION ROLLBACK
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  IMPORTANT: Database rollbacks are the most dangerous type. Always verify
  the rollback migration before running it.

  USING DRIZZLE:
  Drizzle does not have built-in rollback. You must create a reverse migration.

  STEPS:
  1. Identify the problematic migration:
     $ ls apps/backend/drizzle/

  2. Create a reverse migration manually:
     - If migration added a column: CREATE migration to DROP that column
     - If migration added a table: CREATE migration to DROP that table
     - If migration modified data: CREATE migration to reverse the data change

  3. Test the reverse migration on a staging database FIRST:
     $ npx tsx node_modules/drizzle-kit/bin.cjs push --force

  4. Apply to production:
     $ npx tsx node_modules/drizzle-kit/bin.cjs push --force

  5. Restart the API to pick up schema changes:
     $ docker restart unjynx-api

  BACKUP BEFORE ANY MIGRATION:
  $ docker exec unjynx-postgres pg_dump -U unjynx -Fc unjynx > \
    backup-$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M%S).dump

  RESTORE FROM BACKUP:
  $ docker exec -i unjynx-postgres pg_restore -U unjynx -d unjynx --clean \
    < backup-YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS.dump

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  5.4: EMERGENCY MAINTENANCE MODE
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  If the issue cannot be quickly resolved, enable maintenance mode:

  1. API maintenance mode (returns 503 with retry-after header):
     - Set MAINTENANCE_MODE=true in environment
     - Restart: $ docker restart unjynx-api
     - All endpoints return: { "error": "Service under maintenance",
       "retryAfter": 300 }

  2. Mobile app maintenance banner:
     - Update remote config to show maintenance banner
     - Banner text: "We are performing scheduled maintenance. Be back soon."
     - App remains functional offline (offline-first architecture)

  3. Status page update (see Communication Templates)

================================================================================
  6. COMMUNICATION TEMPLATES
================================================================================

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  6.1: STATUS PAGE UPDATE - INVESTIGATING
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  TITLE: [Component] - Investigating Issues

  BODY:
  We are investigating reports of [brief description of the issue].
  Some users may experience [specific symptoms].

  We are actively working on this and will provide updates as we learn more.

  Affected services: [list affected services]
  Started at: [timestamp in IST]

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  6.2: STATUS PAGE UPDATE - IDENTIFIED
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  TITLE: [Component] - Issue Identified

  BODY:
  We have identified the cause of [brief description].
  [One sentence explaining root cause at a high level].

  Our engineering team is implementing a fix. We expect to resolve this
  within [estimated time].

  Affected services: [list]
  Impact: [percentage of users affected, or "all users"]
  Started at: [timestamp]

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  6.3: STATUS PAGE UPDATE - MONITORING
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  TITLE: [Component] - Fix Deployed, Monitoring

  BODY:
  A fix has been deployed for [brief description].
  We are monitoring the situation to ensure stability.

  If you continue to experience issues, please try:
  1. Force-close and reopen the UNJYNX app
  2. Check your internet connection
  3. Contact support@unjynx.app if the issue persists

  Resolution time: [duration]

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  6.4: STATUS PAGE UPDATE - RESOLVED
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  TITLE: [Component] - Resolved

  BODY:
  The issue with [brief description] has been resolved.
  All services are operating normally.

  Root cause: [brief, non-technical explanation]
  Duration: [start time] to [end time] ([total duration])
  Impact: [who was affected and how]

  We apologize for any inconvenience. We are taking steps to prevent
  similar issues in the future.

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  6.5: USER NOTIFICATION (Push / Email)
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  SUBJECT: UNJYNX Service Update

  BODY:
  Hi [Name],

  You may have noticed some issues with [affected feature] earlier today.
  We have identified and resolved the problem. Everything is back to normal.

  If you have any pending reminders that were delayed, they will be delivered
  shortly. No action is needed on your part.

  We take reliability seriously and are implementing additional safeguards
  to prevent this from happening again.

  Thank you for your patience.

  -- The UNJYNX Team

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  6.6: INTERNAL INCIDENT DECLARATION
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

  CHANNEL: #incidents

  @here INCIDENT DECLARED
  Severity: P[0/1/2]
  Summary: [one line description]
  Impact: [who is affected, what is broken]
  Started: [timestamp]
  On-call: [name]
  Status: Investigating
  Tracking: [link to incident doc/issue]

================================================================================
  7. POSTMORTEM TEMPLATE
================================================================================

  ============================================================================
  INCIDENT POSTMORTEM
  ============================================================================

  INCIDENT ID:      INC-YYYY-NNN
  DATE:             YYYY-MM-DD
  SEVERITY:         P[0/1/2]
  DURATION:         [X hours Y minutes]
  AUTHORS:          [names of engineers who investigated]
  STATUS:           [Draft / Reviewed / Final]

  ============================================================================
  SUMMARY
  ============================================================================

  [2-3 sentences describing what happened, the impact, and the resolution.
  Written so that anyone in the company can understand it.]

  ============================================================================
  TIMELINE (all times in IST)
  ============================================================================

  HH:MM  [Event description]
  HH:MM  [Event description]
  HH:MM  Alert fired: [alert name]
  HH:MM  On-call [name] acknowledged
  HH:MM  Severity escalated from P2 to P1
  HH:MM  Root cause identified: [brief]
  HH:MM  Fix deployed
  HH:MM  Verified fix, monitoring
  HH:MM  Incident resolved

  ============================================================================
  ROOT CAUSE
  ============================================================================

  [Detailed technical explanation of what caused the incident. Be specific.
  Include relevant code paths, configuration values, and infrastructure
  details. This section is for engineers.]

  ============================================================================
  IMPACT
  ============================================================================

  Users affected:     [number or percentage]
  Requests failed:    [number]
  Duration:           [X hours Y minutes]
  Revenue impact:     [if applicable]
  Data loss:          [yes/no, details if yes]
  SLA breach:         [yes/no]

  Features affected:
  - [Feature 1]: [how it was affected]
  - [Feature 2]: [how it was affected]

  ============================================================================
  DETECTION
  ============================================================================

  How was the incident detected?
  - [ ] Automated alert (Sentry / Grafana)
  - [ ] User report
  - [ ] Internal testing
  - [ ] Scheduled check

  Time to detect (TTD): [X minutes from start to first alert]
  Time to acknowledge (TTA): [X minutes from alert to acknowledgment]
  Time to mitigate (TTM): [X minutes from acknowledgment to impact reduction]
  Time to resolve (TTR): [X minutes from acknowledgment to full resolution]

  ============================================================================
  WHAT WENT WELL
  ============================================================================

  - [thing that went well]
  - [thing that went well]
  - [thing that went well]

  ============================================================================
  WHAT WENT WRONG
  ============================================================================

  - [thing that went wrong]
  - [thing that went wrong]
  - [thing that went wrong]

  ============================================================================
  WHERE WE GOT LUCKY
  ============================================================================

  - [thing that could have been worse but was not]

  ============================================================================
  ACTION ITEMS
  ============================================================================

  +----+------+-------------------------------------------+-------+----------+
  | #  | Type | Action Item                               | Owner | Due Date |
  +----+------+-------------------------------------------+-------+----------+
  | 1  | Fix  | [description of fix/improvement]          | [who] | [when]   |
  | 2  | Prev | [preventive measure]                      | [who] | [when]   |
  | 3  | Det  | [improve detection/alerting]               | [who] | [when]   |
  | 4  | Proc | [process improvement]                     | [who] | [when]   |
  +----+------+-------------------------------------------+-------+----------+

  Types: Fix = direct fix, Prev = prevent recurrence, Det = improve detection,
         Proc = process change

  ============================================================================
  LESSONS LEARNED
  ============================================================================

  [1-3 key takeaways that the team should internalize. These should be
  actionable insights, not blame assignments. Focus on systemic improvements.]

  ============================================================================
  APPENDIX
  ============================================================================

  Relevant logs:
  [paste key log lines]

  Relevant metrics:
  [link to Grafana dashboard snapshot]

  Related incidents:
  [links to similar past incidents, if any]

  ============================================================================
  BLAMELESS POSTMORTEM PRINCIPLES
  ============================================================================

  This postmortem follows blameless principles:
  - We focus on systemic causes, not individual mistakes
  - We assume everyone acted with the best information available at the time
  - We look for process and tooling improvements, not personnel changes
  - The goal is to learn and prevent recurrence, not to assign blame
